package com.routinely.app.data;

public class MindsetData {

    /** 30 daily lessons from Atomic Habits by James Clear. Each entry: {title, body}. */
    public static final String[][] DAILY_LESSONS = {
        {"The 1% Rule",
         "You don't rise to the level of your goals, you fall to the level of your systems. Tiny improvements of just 1% each day compound into extraordinary results over the long run.\n\nIf you get 1% better each day for one year, you'll end up 37 times better by the time you're done. Conversely, if you get 1% worse each day for one year, you'll decline nearly down to zero.\n\nSuccess is the product of daily habits — not once-in-a-lifetime transformations. Focus on the trajectory, not the current results."},

        {"Identity-Based Habits",
         "The real reason habits matter is not what you achieve but who you become. Outcomes are about what you get, processes are about what you do, and identity is about what you believe.\n\nEvery action you take is a vote for the type of person you wish to become. The goal is not to read a book; the goal is to become a reader. Not to run a marathon — to become a runner.\n\nFocus on building identity first. Ask: 'What would a healthy person do?' or 'What would a disciplined person do?' Let identity guide behavior."},

        {"The Habit Loop",
         "All habits follow a four-step pattern: Cue → Craving → Response → Reward. The cue triggers a craving, which motivates a response, which provides a reward that satisfies the craving.\n\nYou cannot get rid of a bad habit, only replace it. Keep the same cue and reward but change the response. Understanding the loop gives you leverage over any behavior.\n\nTo build a good habit: make the cue obvious, the craving attractive, the response easy, and the reward satisfying. To break a bad habit: reverse each law."},

        {"Implementation Intentions",
         "People who make a specific plan for when and where they will act are more likely to follow through. Research calls this an implementation intention: 'I will [BEHAVIOR] at [TIME] in [LOCATION].'\n\nVague intentions like 'I'll exercise more' almost never work. Specific plans like 'I will run at 7 AM in the park on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday' double or triple follow-through rates.\n\nBe precise. Link your habit to a time and place. The more specific your intention, the more likely you are to act."},

        {"Habit Stacking",
         "One of the best ways to build a new habit is to identify an existing habit you do each day and then stack your new behavior on top. This is called habit stacking.\n\nThe formula: 'After I [CURRENT HABIT], I will [NEW HABIT].' For example: 'After I pour my morning coffee, I will write in my journal for one minute.'\n\nHabit stacking works because existing habits serve as reliable cues. You are tying your new behavior to an already-established trigger."},

        {"Design Your Environment",
         "The environment is the invisible hand that shapes your behavior. You don't have to be the victim of your environment — you can be the architect of it.\n\nEvery habit is initiated by a cue. Make good habits obvious by placing cues in your environment. Want to eat healthier? Put fruit on the counter. Want to read more? Leave a book on your pillow.\n\nDesigning your environment for success is more powerful than relying on willpower. When your environment changes, your behavior changes."},

        {"Self-Control Is Overrated",
         "People who appear to have great self-control are typically those who need to use it least. They structure their lives so they don't need willpower.\n\nSelf-control is a short-term strategy. You can only resist temptation so many times before you give in. The reliable path is to cut bad habits off at the source by reducing exposure to the cue.\n\nThis is the secret to self-control: make the cues of your bad habits invisible. Out of sight, out of mind. Redesign your life to avoid the things that tempt you."},

        {"Temptation Bundling",
         "Temptation bundling works by linking an action you want to do with an action you need to do. You're more likely to find a behavior attractive if you get to do one of your favorite things at the same time.\n\nExample: 'I will only watch Netflix while exercising.' Or: 'I will only check social media after completing 30 minutes of focused work.'\n\nPair something you need to do with something you enjoy. This makes habits more attractive and easier to sustain."},

        {"Join a Winning Culture",
         "We imitate the habits of three groups: the close (family and friends), the many (the tribe), and the powerful (those with status). One of the most effective things you can do to build better habits is to join a culture where your desired behavior is the normal behavior.\n\nNothing sustains motivation better than belonging to a group where your desired identity is the norm. If everyone around you is fit, healthy, or hardworking, it's easier to stay consistent.\n\nSurround yourself with people who have the habits you want to develop. Your culture sets the expectations."},

        {"Reframe Your Mindset",
         "Instead of thinking 'I have to exercise,' try thinking 'I get to exercise.' Instead of 'I have to prepare my notes,' say 'I get to prepare my notes.'\n\nThis subtle shift in language reframes habits as opportunities rather than burdens. Many habits that feel like obstacles are actually privileges — ways to improve health, build wealth, strengthen relationships.\n\nHighlight the benefits of good habits rather than the drawbacks. Associate good habits with positive feelings and they become self-sustaining."},

        {"Reduce Friction",
         "The amount of friction associated with a habit determines how often it occurs. Every extra step between you and a habit slightly reduces the probability of doing it.\n\nBusiness is not required — laziness is natural. Work with your nature, not against it. Decrease the number of steps between you and your good habits.\n\nPrime your environment: lay out your gym clothes the night before, keep healthy food at eye level, pre-load what you need for your morning routine. Reduce friction to zero."},

        {"The Law of Least Effort",
         "Human beings naturally gravitate toward the option requiring least effort. This is why environment design is so powerful — it changes the path of least resistance.\n\nAdd friction to your bad habits and remove friction from your good ones. Make the easy choice the good choice. Want to eat less junk food? Don't buy it. Want to read more? Place books everywhere.\n\nYour habits are essentially the choices you make when the cost of resistance is at its lowest. Design your environment so the right choice is also the easy one."},

        {"The Two-Minute Rule",
         "When you start a new habit, it should take less than two minutes to do. 'Read before bed each night' becomes 'Read one page.' 'Do 30 minutes of yoga' becomes 'Take out my yoga mat.'\n\nThe idea is to make your habits as easy as possible to start. A habit must be established before it can be improved. Standardize before you optimize.\n\nThe two-minute rule isn't about doing tiny things forever — it's about mastering the art of showing up. Once you've started, you'll often continue naturally."},

        {"Make It Hard",
         "A commitment device is a choice you make now that controls your future behavior. It locks you in to good choices before temptation strikes.\n\nDelete social media apps from your phone. Use a website blocker during work hours. Prepare healthy food on Sundays so junk food is less accessible. Increase friction for bad habits.\n\nThe best way to eliminate a bad habit is to make it nearly impossible to do. One-time actions that lock in future behavior are among the most powerful tools for change."},

        {"The Cardinal Rule of Behavior Change",
         "What is immediately rewarded is repeated. What is immediately punished is avoided. This is the cardinal rule of behavior change.\n\nThe biggest challenge in building habits is that most good habits have costs in the present and rewards in the future. Most bad habits are the opposite. The brain values the present moment more than the future.\n\nAdd immediate rewards to your good habits. Track your progress, celebrate small wins, give yourself positive reinforcement after completing a habit. Make the benefits feel immediate."},

        {"Never Miss Twice",
         "The first rule of habit mastery: never miss once. The second rule: if you miss once, never miss twice. Missing once is an accident; missing twice is the start of a new bad habit.\n\nPerfection is not the goal. You will miss a day. Life gets in the way. The key is to get back on track immediately. A bad workout is infinitely better than no workout.\n\nShowing up — even when it's hard, even imperfectly — is how streaks survive. The habit of not breaking habits is the most important habit of all."},

        {"Habit Tracking",
         "One of the most satisfying feelings is the feeling of making progress. Habit tracking provides a visual cue reminding you to act, a record of your effort, and a source of immediate satisfaction.\n\n'Don't break the chain' is the simple idea behind habit tracking. Mark an X on a calendar each day you complete your habit. Keep the chain going.\n\nTracking creates evidence of your progress and proof that you are the type of person who follows through. It moves the reward closer to the behavior, making habits more attractive."},

        {"Accountability Partners",
         "An accountability partner creates an immediate cost to inaction. Knowing someone else is watching changes everything. We care deeply about what others think of us.\n\nAn accountability contract is a written agreement stating your commitment, your goal, and the consequences for failing to follow through. Sharing this with a trusted person significantly increases follow-through.\n\nHabit contracts may feel rigid, but they clarify expectations and make the cost of bad behavior visible. Pairing internal motivation with external accountability is a powerful combination."},

        {"Genes and Habits",
         "Genes don't determine your destiny — they determine your areas of opportunity. Some people are naturally inclined toward athletic performance, creative pursuits, or intellectual work. Work with your nature.\n\nThe secret to maximizing your potential is to choose habits that align with your natural inclinations. What feels like a burden to others should feel like play to you.\n\nExplore, experiment, and find what fits. When you can't win by being better, win by being different. Habits stick when they align with who you naturally are."},

        {"The Goldilocks Rule",
         "Humans experience peak motivation when working on tasks that are right at the edge of their current abilities — not too hard, not too easy. This is the Goldilocks Rule.\n\nWhen you're bored, you quit. When you're anxious, you quit. When you're in the sweet spot — challenged but not overwhelmed — you stay engaged. The greatest threat to success is often not failure but boredom.\n\nKeep your habits on the edge of your ability. Raise the difficulty slightly as you improve. Constantly seek the next level of challenge to maintain engagement."},

        {"Fall in Love with Boredom",
         "The differentiator between professionals and amateurs is the ability to show up and work even when it's boring. The pros don't love it every day — they do it anyway.\n\nEvery habit becomes routine eventually. The exciting novelty wears off. The real work begins when you fall in love with the process — not because it's always exciting, but because you are committed to the identity behind it.\n\nAnyone can work hard when motivated. The ability to work when you don't feel like it is what builds mastery. Embrace the boredom as part of the path."},

        {"Systems Beat Goals",
         "Goals are about the results you want to achieve. Systems are about the processes that lead to those results. Both winners and losers have the same goals — what sets them apart is their systems.\n\nAchieving a goal only changes your life for the moment. To improve for good, you need to solve the system problem, not the goal problem. Fix the inputs and the outputs fix themselves.\n\nFocus on the system, not the score. Build the machine, not just the single outcome. Habits are the atoms of your system."},

        {"The Plateau of Latent Potential",
         "Habits often seem to make no difference until you cross a critical threshold. The early and middle stages of any new pursuit offer little visible progress. This is the Plateau of Latent Potential.\n\nIce stays frozen until it reaches 32°F, then suddenly changes state. All the work done in the cold was not wasted — it was building up to the transformation.\n\nYour habits are compounding beneath the surface. Trust the process even when results are invisible. Breakthrough moments are preceded by a long period of buildup. Be patient."},

        {"Marginal Gains",
         "The aggregation of marginal gains: search for a 1% improvement in everything you do. Improve sleep, nutrition, training, recovery, mindset — even by a tiny amount each — and the combined impact becomes remarkable.\n\nThis is how small habits compound into outsized results. You don't need to do anything extreme. You just need to never stop making tiny improvements.\n\nMarginal gains are invisible in the moment but profound over time. The system of daily 1% improvements is more powerful than any single dramatic change."},

        {"Decisive Moments",
         "Every day there are a handful of moments that deliver an outsized impact — decisive moments that set the course of your actions for hours to come.\n\nChoosing to go to the gym instead of the couch is a decisive moment. It's not just a single action; it activates a chain of productive behaviors. One good choice leads to another.\n\nPay attention to the fork-in-the-road moments of your day. A two-minute habit started at the right moment can change everything that follows. Master the decisive moments and you'll master your day."},

        {"Habit Shaping",
         "Habits can be built in stages. You don't need to perform the final behavior from day one — you can gradually shape your behavior toward the ultimate goal.\n\nWalking into the gym is step one. Changing into workout clothes is step two. Doing a light warm-up is step three. Each step makes the next one easier. You're building momentum.\n\nFocus on getting 1% of the way there, then 2%, then 3%. Each small action you take is a foothold toward the complete behavior. Mastery is built one tiny step at a time."},

        {"Layer Your Identity",
         "The deepest form of change is identity change. Outcomes change what you have. Processes change what you do. Identity changes who you are.\n\nYour behaviors are simply a reflection of your current identity. What you do now is a mirror of the type of person you believe that you are. To change your behavior for good, start believing new things about yourself.\n\n'I'm trying to quit smoking' vs 'I'm not a smoker.' 'I'm trying to run more' vs 'I'm a runner.' The words you use to describe yourself shape who you become."},

        {"Process Over Outcome",
         "Winners and losers often share the same goals — what differs is their system. Goals narrow your focus. Systems expand what's possible.\n\nIf you're focused only on the goal, you'll keep delaying happiness until you reach it. 'I'll be happy when I lose 20 pounds.' 'I'll be happy when I finish the book.' The path is the destination.\n\nFall in love with the process. Build systems you're proud of. When you fall in love with daily practice rather than the prize, the prize eventually comes as a byproduct."},

        {"Habits and Freedom",
         "The purpose of habits is to free up your mental bandwidth for more creative work. Habits are the foundation — they handle the routine so your mind can focus on what matters.\n\nAn athlete with automatic fundamentals can focus on strategy. A musician with automatic technique can focus on expression. A person with automatic healthy habits can focus on everything else.\n\nBuilding good habits is not about restriction — it's about liberation. Discipline is the path to freedom. The more you automate the good, the more mental energy you have for what truly matters."},

        {"Annual Review",
         "Once a year, conduct a thorough review of your habits. Ask: What went well? What didn't go well? What did I learn? How do I want to approach next year differently?\n\nThis is not about harsh self-judgment — it's about honest reflection. Habits that served you well at one stage of life may need to evolve. Goals that once excited you may no longer fit your current values.\n\nSchedule time for reflection. The habits you review are the habits you improve. Systems that are reviewed are systems that evolve. Growth requires honest assessment."},

        {"Keep Evolving",
         "The tighter you cling to an identity, the harder it becomes to grow beyond it. The very identity you used to build a good habit can become an anchor preventing further growth.\n\nStay curious. Revisit your habits regularly. Ask whether they still serve your goals. What got you here might not get you to the next level — and that's okay.\n\nMastery requires both consistency and adaptability. Hold your habits lightly enough to change them when needed, and firmly enough to maintain them when the process is hard. Keep evolving."}
    };

    /** Library articles for each section. Index [section][article]: {title, read_time, body}. */
    public static final String[][][] LIBRARY = {
        // 0: Atoms 101
        {
            {"How to Build a New Habit: This is Your Strategy Guide", "10 min",
             "Building a new habit requires more than willpower. James Clear's research shows that habits form through a four-step loop: Cue → Craving → Response → Reward. Every habit starts with a cue that triggers a craving, which motivates a response, which delivers a reward.\n\nThe key is design, not discipline. Start with an implementation intention — a specific plan for when and where you'll act: 'I will [BEHAVIOR] at [TIME] in [LOCATION].' This simple technique doubles or triples your follow-through rate.\n\nMake the habit obvious, attractive, easy, and satisfying. Stack it onto an existing routine: 'After I pour my morning coffee, I will write one sentence in my journal.' Design your environment so cues for good habits are visible and accessible.\n\nRemember the two-minute rule: scale the new habit down until it takes less than two minutes to start. Standardize before you optimize. The goal is to show up consistently and cast votes for the identity of the person you want to become."},
            {"Identity-Based Habits: How to Actually Stick to Your Goals", "10 min",
             "Most people try to change habits by focusing on outcomes — lose weight, write a book, earn more money. But the most effective way to change behavior is to focus on who you want to become, not what you want to achieve.\n\nOutcomes are about what you get. Processes are about what you do. Identity is about what you believe. Identity-based habits start with asking: What kind of person do I want to be? Then prove it to yourself with small consistent wins.\n\nEvery action you take is a vote for the type of person you wish to become. Two votes won't transform you, but as the votes pile up, the evidence changes. Your identity emerges out of your habits. You become your habits.\n\nStart by deciding who you want to be, then prove it with small actions. 'I'm trying to exercise' is weak. 'I'm a person who exercises' changes everything."}
        },
        // 1: Productivity
        {
            {"What is Your \"Average Speed\" in Life, Health, and Work?", "5 min",
             "Imagine two people. Person A goes on a crash diet — intense for a week, then gives up. Person B eats slightly better every single day for a year. Who makes more progress? The math is clear: the slow, steady person wins overwhelmingly.\n\nYour average speed — not your peak intensity — determines your long-term results. One week of hard work is dwarfed by one year of consistent effort. Most people overestimate what they can do in a week and underestimate what they can do in a year.\n\nFocus on your baseline: your average daily action. A professional writer who writes 300 words a day every day produces 109,500 words a year — more than a novel. A person who walks 30 minutes a day accumulates 182 hours of exercise annually.\n\nRaise your floor, not just your ceiling. Build systems that make your default behavior a good behavior. Your average speed is your most powerful metric."},
            {"You Get 25,000 Mornings: 8 Ways Not to Waste Them", "7 min",
             "The average person lives about 25,000 days as an adult. Each morning is a unit of life — a fresh window of time, energy, and focus. How you spend your mornings shapes the person you become.\n\n1. Start the night before. Lay out clothes, prep food, plan tomorrow. 2. Wake before the world asks something of you. 3. Protect the first hour — no email, no social media. 4. Begin with movement to activate body and mind. 5. Do your most important creative or cognitive work first.\n\n6. Build a 'morning anchor' — one habit that grounds the rest. 7. Review your identity and goals briefly. 8. Make your bed — it signals that order matters to you.\n\nYour morning routine is not just a productivity hack. It is a declaration of what matters. Each morning you choose who you are before the world gets a chance to choose for you. Use these 25,000 mornings wisely."}
        },
        // 2: Self-Improvement
        {
            {"Identity-Based Habits: How to Actually Stick to Your Goals This Year", "10 min",
             "New Year's resolutions fail because they focus on outcomes rather than identity. 'I want to lose weight' fails. 'I am a healthy person' succeeds — because it changes the filter through which you make decisions all day long.\n\nIdentity change is the north star. Start by deciding the type of person you want to be. Then ask: what would that person do right now? What would a consistent writer do? A healthy eater? A focused professional?\n\nEvery small action in alignment with your desired identity strengthens that identity. Every vote cast for your better self makes it more real. The goal is not a specific outcome — it is a specific self.\n\nThis year, instead of setting goals, set identity. Not 'I want to read more books' but 'I am a person who reads every day.' Not 'I want to exercise' but 'I am an athlete.' Watch how everything else follows."},
            {"Why is it So Hard to Build Good Habits?", "7 min",
             "Good habits are hard to build because the rewards are delayed and the costs are immediate. Eating well means resisting delicious but unhealthy food right now for a healthier body months later. The brain is wired to prioritize the present.\n\nBad habits are easy because they deliver immediate pleasure. Good habits require patience because the reward is in the future. This is the fundamental tension of behavior change.\n\nThe solution is to add immediate rewards to good habits. Track your progress visually. Celebrate completing a habit — even briefly. Use a habit contract to add immediate accountability. Make the benefits feel real right now, not just later.\n\nAlso: reduce the friction of starting. When it's too easy to not do something, most people won't. Remove every possible barrier. Prepare in advance. Make the first step trivially small. Start before you're ready, because ready never comes."}
        },
        // 3: Goal Setting
        {
            {"Identity-Based Habits: How to Actually Stick to Your Goals This Year", "10 min",
             "Setting better goals starts with understanding what goals can and cannot do. Goals set direction. Systems produce results. If you want to build better habits, focus on the system — not the goal itself.\n\nA goal says where you want to go. A system says how you'll get there and what you'll do when the path gets hard. People with the same goal achieve wildly different results because they have different systems.\n\nThe most powerful goal you can set is an identity goal: deciding what type of person you want to become. Then your daily systems are simply the actions that person takes. Your habits become a reflection of your identity.\n\nThis is why New Year's resolutions often fail — they focus on outcomes, not systems or identity. This year, build the system. Become the person. The goal will follow."},
            {"How to Achieve Your Goals More Easily", "4 min",
             "The easiest path to achieving your goals is to make them inevitable. Design your environment so the default action moves you toward your goal. Remove friction. Add cues. Build systems.\n\nReduce the number of decisions required each day. Every decision is a potential point of failure. Automate what you can — meal prep on Sundays, gym time blocked in the calendar, books next to the couch.\n\nBuild what researchers call 'bright lines' — rules so clear that there's no ambiguity about what to do. 'I never eat junk food on weekdays' is clearer than 'I try to eat healthily.' Bright lines remove the need to negotiate with yourself.\n\nFinally: make goals identity-based rather than outcome-based. You are not working toward a result — you are becoming someone. When your identity aligns with your goal, achievement feels inevitable."}
        },
        // 4: Willpower
        {
            {"How to Stick to Your Goals When Life Gets Crazy", "6 min",
             "Life will always throw obstacles at you. The people who succeed long-term are not those who never face disruption — they are those who have systems for returning to their habits after disruption.\n\nThe key insight: don't try to maintain perfection. Aim for consistency over time. The 'never miss twice' rule is your lifeline. If you miss a day, get back on track the next day. One bad day doesn't define you; missing a week might.\n\nBuild 'minimum viable habits' — stripped-down versions of your full habit for hard days. Instead of a full workout, do 10 push-ups. Instead of writing 500 words, write one sentence. Showing up, even minimally, maintains the identity and the streak.\n\nFinally: build recovery into your system. Know in advance what you'll do when things go wrong. Have a contingency plan. People who survive disruption are the ones who planned for it."},
            {"How Will You Measure Your Life?", "8 min",
             "Clayton Christensen famously asked: How will you measure your life? Not just your career, but your relationships, your health, your character — the full picture of a life well lived.\n\nMost people apply careful thought to their professional lives but default their personal lives to whatever feels easiest in the moment. The habits we build in our personal lives are just as important — perhaps more important — than our professional achievements.\n\nJames Clear's atomic habits framework applies equally to life design. What identity do you want to have in your relationships? What habits would that person practice? What systems would support a fulfilling life, not just a successful career?\n\nAllocate your resources — time, energy, attention — with the same intentionality you apply to work. The habits you build in private shape the person you bring to every relationship and every challenge. Measure your life by who you are becoming."}
        },
        // 5: Motivation
        {
            {"How to Get Motivated When You Don't Feel Like It", "7 min",
             "Motivation is not a reliable force. It comes and goes, peaks and valleys, rises with novelty and falls with routine. The mistake is waiting to feel motivated before starting.\n\nAction causes motivation, not the other way around. Start before you feel ready. Once you begin, motivation often appears. The hardest part is starting — the first two minutes are the most difficult. Use the two-minute rule to get started.\n\nAnother strategy: pair your habits with things you enjoy (temptation bundling). Only listen to your favorite podcast while exercising. Only watch shows you love while doing chores. Associate good behaviors with positive feelings.\n\nFinally: connect your habits to your identity. You don't need to feel motivated to be a runner — you simply act like a runner. Identity-driven action transcends motivation. When the feeling isn't there, your identity is."},
            {"Get Back on Track: 7 Strategies When Motivation Fades", "8 min",
             "Motivation fades for everyone — even the most disciplined people. The difference is that consistent people have strategies for recovery. Here are seven approaches:\n\n1. Never miss twice. One bad day is an accident; two starts a new habit. 2. Lower the bar. Do the minimum viable version of your habit. 3. Remove friction. Make the right thing easier to do than the wrong thing.\n\n4. Change your environment. A new setting creates fresh energy. 5. Return to your identity. Ask: 'What would a [runner/writer/healthy person] do right now?' 6. Review your progress. Looking back at how far you've come reignites motivation.\n\n7. Recommit publicly. Tell someone. An accountability partner adds external pressure. Motivation is a renewable resource — these strategies help you find it again quickly."}
        }
    };
}
